(1) The President and members of the Tribunal shall hold office for a period not exceeding three years and shall be eligible for reappointment.
(2) The President and a member may resign from office by giving not less than one month's written notice to the Minister.
(3) The Minister may terminate the appointment of the President or a member if the President or member—
(a) is unable to perform his functions due to infirmity;
(b) is declared a bankrupt;
(c) is convicted of an offence;
(d) is guilty of misconduct; or
(e) has contravened the terms and conditions of appointment.

(1) Any person who is aggrieved by—
(a) a decision of the Commissioner to refuse registration or renewal of registration;
(b) a decision of the Commissioner to cancel or suspend a registration;
(c) the service of an enforcement notice;
(d) any other decision of the Commissioner made under this Act that is specified in regulations,
may appeal to the Tribunal.
(2) An appeal must be made within thirty days of the date on which the appellant is notified of the decision being appealed.
(3) An appeal shall be made in the prescribed form and shall be accompanied by the prescribed fee.

(1) The Tribunal shall have the same power to punish for contempt as a superior court.
(2) A person commits contempt of the Tribunal if the person—
(a) disobeys an order of the Tribunal;
(b) interferes with or obstructs any proceedings of the Tribunal;
(c) publishes any matter which interferes with or obstructs the administration of justice by the Tribunal.
(3) A person who commits contempt of the Tribunal may be punished by the Tribunal with a fine not exceeding five thousand ringgit or imprisonment not exceeding six months.

(1) The Minister may make rules governing the practice and procedure of the Tribunal, including rules relating to—
(a) the form and manner of applications;
(b) the giving of notices;
(c) the conduct of hearings;
(d) the payment of fees and expenses;
(e) any other matters relating to the Tribunal's functions.
(2) Until rules are made under this section, the Tribunal may adopt such procedure as it considers appropriate.
